agentlog`, a shared GitMeta helper, or direct `git-meta-lib`\n   usage. Current preference: use GitMeta transport helpers for fetch, then\n   `but-agentlog` for interpretation.\n2. **Projection contract.** Define the server-facing output from\n   `but-agentlog`: related sessions, related turns, record previews, exact\n   drill-down, relevance evidence, and redaction guarantees.\n3. **PR-to-targe\n[TRUNCATED]\nion turns captured local agentlog\n   data into review-visible Agent Trail data. URL replacement alone must not\n   publish private context.\n5. **Session selection and ranking.** Decide which related sessions appear by\n   default, how turns are highlighted, and how the UI explains relevance without\n   claiming authorship.\n6. **Session browsing UX.** Lock the first-page structure: overview, sessions,\n   turn timeline, grouped records, validation, open questions, and raw evidence\n   drawer.\n7. **Failure states.** Define what the page shows for no access, no captured\n    data, weak relation evidence, redaction failures, too much data, and stale\n    GitMeta.\n8. **Retention and caching.** Decide whether generated trails are stored,\n    invalidated, expired, or rebuilt on demand.\n9. **Out-of-scope line.** Explicitly exclude compliance/audit guarantees,\n    full transcript publishing by default, automatic private publication, and\n    model-generated summaries as the source of truth.\n\nThe smallest buildable slice should prove the full path without solving every\nfuture policy:\n\n```text\nGitHub PR URL -> public access check -> metadata fetch -> but-agentlog lookup\n-> review-safe snapshot -> overview page -> session/turn drill-down\n```\n\nIf that path is vague, implementation should wait.\n\n## Remaining Answers Needed\n\nThe big shape is clear enough now: Forge-hosted, public-repo v1, on-demand URL\nentry, generated snapshots, server-side repo cache, GitMeta fetch, and\n`but-agentlog` interpretation.\n\nBefore building, the remaining questions are:\n